## Great Scenario! Let's Analyze Each Stage

```
30k XML Records
      │
      ▼
Parse & Transform to Object    ← CPU bound
      │
      ▼
Batch of 200 → Salesforce API  ← I/O bound (blocking)
      │
      ▼
Update DB per record           ← I/O bound (blocking)
```

---

## Stage by Stage Analysis

### Stage 1 — XML Parsing (CPU Bound)
```java
// Virtual threads give ZERO benefit here
// Pure CPU work — they never unmount anyway
// ForkJoinPool / parallel streams is better

List<CustomObject> objects = xmlRecords.parallelStream()
    .map(xml -> parseAndTransform(xml)) // CPU work
    .toList();
// 30k records, uses all CPU cores efficiently ✅
```

---

### Stage 2 — Salesforce API in Batches of 200 (I/O Bound)
```java
// 30k / 200 = 150 API calls
// Each call blocks waiting for Salesforce response
// THIS is where virtual threads shine!

ExecutorService vExec = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor();

List<List<CustomObject>> batches = partition(objects, 200); // 150 batches

List<CompletableFuture<SalesforceResponse>> futures = batches.stream()
    .map(batch -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(
        () -> callSalesforceAPI(batch), vExec  // 150 concurrent API calls
    ))
    .toList();

CompletableFuture.allOf(futures.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0])).join();
```

```
Without virtual threads (say 8 platform threads):
150 API calls / 8 threads = ~19 rounds
If each API takes 2s → 19 × 2s = 38 seconds ❌

With virtual threads:
All 150 calls fire concurrently
Total time ≈ 2s (one API call duration) ✅
```

---

### Stage 3 — DB Update (I/O Bound)
```java
// Based on Salesforce response, update DB per record
// Again blocking I/O — virtual threads help

futures.stream()
    .map(CompletableFuture::join)
    .forEach(response -> {
        CompletableFuture.runAsync(
            () -> updateDb(response), vExec // concurrent DB updates
        );
    });
```

---

## But Wait — Real Concerns Here! ⚠️

### 1. Salesforce API Rate Limits
```java
// ❌ BAD — firing all 150 batches at once may hit rate limits
CompletableFuture.allOf(all150Futures).join();

// ✅ BETTER — use a semaphore to control concurrency
Semaphore semaphore = new Semaphore(10); // max 10 concurrent calls

List<CompletableFuture<SalesforceResponse>> futures = batches.stream()
    .map(batch -> CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        semaphore.acquire();
        try {
            return callSalesforceAPI(batch);
        } finally {
            semaphore.release();
        }
    }, vExec))
    .toList();
```

### 2. DB Connection Pool Exhaustion
```java
// ❌ BAD — 30k virtual threads hammering DB simultaneously
// DB connection pool is typically 10-50 connections

// ✅ BETTER — separate executor with limits for DB
ExecutorService dbExec = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(20); // match pool size

CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> updateDb(record), dbExec);
```

### 3. Memory — 30k Objects in Memory
```java
// ❌ BAD — loading all 30k records at once
List<CustomObject> all = parseAll30kRecords();

// ✅ BETTER — stream/chunk the XML processing
streamXmlRecords()          // process in chunks
    .buffer(200)            // batch of 200
    .forEach(batch -> processBatch(batch));
```

---

## Recommended Architecture

```
30k XML Records (streamed, not all at once)
         │
         ▼
  Chunk of 200 records
         │
         ▼ (parallelStream — CPU work)
  Parse & Transform
         │
         ▼ (Virtual Thread — I/O)
  Salesforce API call  ──── Semaphore(10) to control rate
         │
         ▼ (Fixed Thread Pool matching DB pool size)
  DB Update per record
         │
         ▼
  Next chunk of 200...
```

---

## Final Verdict

| Stage | Virtual Threads? | Why |
|---|---|---|
| XML Parsing | ❌ No | CPU bound, use parallelStream |
| Salesforce API | ✅ Yes | Blocking I/O, 150 concurrent calls |
| DB Update | ⚠️ Careful | Use fixed pool matching DB connections |

> Virtual threads are **great here but not everywhere.**
> The real danger is **Salesforce rate limits** and **DB connection pool exhaustion** — virtual threads make it too easy to fire too many concurrent calls.
> A **Semaphore** is your best friend in this scenario to get concurrency benefits without overwhelming external systems.
